{"parse":{"title":"Death of the novel","pageid":9464575,"revid":860498531,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <i><b>death of the novel</b></i> is the common name for the theoretical discussion of the declining importance of the <a href=\"/wiki/Novel\" title=\"Novel\">novel</a> as <a href=\"/wiki/Literary_form\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literary form\">literary form</a>. Many 20th century authors entered into the debate, often sharing their ideas in their own <a href=\"/wiki/Fiction\" title=\"Fiction\">fiction</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Non-fiction\" title=\"Non-fiction\">non-fiction</a> writings.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Causes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Causes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Critical_response\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Critical response</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Death_of_the_novel&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg/250px-1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"115\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg/375px-1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg/500px-1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2000\" data-file-height=\"922\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:1877-winslow-homer-the-new-novel.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Winslow Homer, \"The New Novel\", 1877</div></div></div>\n<p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Novel\" title=\"Novel\">novel</a> was well-defined by the 19th century.  In the 20th century, however, many writers began to rebel against the traditional structures imposed by this form.  This reaction against the novel caused some literary theorists to question the relevancy of the novel and even to predict its 'death.'\n</p><p>Some of the earliest proponents of the \"death of the novel\" were <a href=\"/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Ortega_y_Gasset\" title=\"Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset\">Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset</a>, who wrote his <i>Decline of the Novel</i> in 1925<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and <a href=\"/wiki/Walter_Benjamin\" title=\"Walter Benjamin\">Walter Benjamin</a> in his 1930 review <i>Krisis des Romans</i> (Crisis of the Novel).<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In the 1950s and 1960s, contributors to the discussion included <a href=\"/wiki/Gore_Vidal\" title=\"Gore Vidal\">Gore Vidal</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Roland_Barthes\" title=\"Roland Barthes\">Roland Barthes</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/John_Barth\" title=\"John Barth\">John Barth</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Ronald_Sukenick\" title=\"Ronald Sukenick\">Ronald Sukenick</a> wrote the story <i>The Death of the Novel</i> in 1969. In 1954, <a href=\"/wiki/Wolfgang_Kayser\" title=\"Wolfgang Kayser\">Wolfgang Kayser</a> argued that the death of the narrator would lead to the death of the novel - a view that has since been contested by many people.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Meanwhile, <a href=\"/wiki/Alain_Robbe-Grillet\" title=\"Alain Robbe-Grillet\">Alain Robbe-Grillet</a> argued that the novel would be likely to atrophy and die as a literary form if it did not advance beyond 19th century structures; this admonition led to his creation of the New Novel or <a href=\"/wiki/Nouveau_roman\" title=\"Nouveau roman\">Nouveau roman</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Tom_Wolfe\" title=\"Tom Wolfe\">Tom Wolfe</a> in the 1970s predicted that the <a href=\"/wiki/New_Journalism\" title=\"New Journalism\">New Journalism</a> would displace the novel. <a href=\"/wiki/Italo_Calvino\" title=\"Italo Calvino\">Italo Calvino</a> is considered to have turned round the question \"is the novel dead?\", as \"is it possible to tell stories that are not novels?\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Causes\">Causes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Death_of_the_novel&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Causes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Cybook Opus Bookeen.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg/250px-Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"188\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg/375px-Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg/500px-Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3456\" data-file-height=\"2592\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Cybook_Opus_Bookeen.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div></div></div></div>\n<p>As for causes, <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_B._Pippin\" title=\"Robert B. Pippin\">Robert B. Pippin</a> connects the 'death of the novel' with the rise of <a href=\"/wiki/Nihilism\" title=\"Nihilism\">nihilism</a> in European culture.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Saul_Bellow\" title=\"Saul Bellow\">Saul Bellow</a>, discussing <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ravelstein\" title=\"Ravelstein\">Ravelstein</a></i> which was loosely a portrait of <a href=\"/wiki/Allan_Bloom\" title=\"Allan Bloom\">Allan Bloom</a>, commented on a connection to the idea that <i>they are really saying that there are no significant people to write about</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On the other hand, <a href=\"/wiki/David_Foster_Wallace\" title=\"David Foster Wallace\">David Foster Wallace</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> connected the 'death of the novel' with the mortality of the post-war generation of American novelists.\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Will_Self\" title=\"Will Self\">Will Self</a> discussed the idea of the death of the novel, as a microcosm of the wider debate about the death of the book itself, in relation to the transition from a <a href=\"/wiki/Johannes_Gutenberg\" title=\"Johannes Gutenberg\">Gutenberg</a> era of printing to the post-Gutenberg era of the information age.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> He has even questioned the longevity of the bookshelf, let alone the book.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Technological change is often identified as a major possible cause. Anxieties about the disappearance of the book, as well as the novel, have been common throughout the <a href=\"/wiki/20th_century\" title=\"20th century\">20th century</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Henry Kannberg sees the post-Gutenberg age as being one where the entire morphology of literature may transform as a result of 'hyper-literacy' and the exponential abundance of texts. He argues that there may be a rebirth of the novel, or the birth of a descendant to it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Similar observations were made by <a href=\"/wiki/Marcus_du_Sautoy\" title=\"Marcus du Sautoy\">Marcus du Sautoy</a> who argued that technology allows for changes to books and novel-writing that are only just beginning to be explored.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Critical_response\">Critical response</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Death_of_the_novel&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Critical response\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Contemporary scholars such as <a href=\"/wiki/Kathleen_Fitzpatrick_(American_academic)\" title=\"Kathleen Fitzpatrick (American academic)\">Kathleen Fitzpatrick</a> argue that claims of the novel's death were highly exaggerated, and that such claims often reflect anxiety about changes in the twentieth-century media landscape, as well as more submerged anxieties about social changes within the United States itself.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>For <a href=\"/wiki/Salman_Rushdie\" title=\"Salman Rushdie\">Salman Rushdie</a>, the postwar notion of the 'death of the novel' is one that has tended to exhibit certain First World assumptions based on imperialistic nostalgia.<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Death_of_the_novel&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Literature_of_Exhaustion\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Literature of Exhaustion\">Literature of Exhaustion</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Death_of_the_novel&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Liukkonen, Petri. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20070205144836/http://kirjasto.sci.fi/grasset.htm\">\"Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset\"</a>. <i>Books and Writers </i>(kirjasto.sci.fi)<i><span></span></i>. Finland: <a href=\"/wiki/Kuusankoski\" title=\"Kuusankoski\">Kuusankoski</a> Public Library. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.kirjasto.sci.fi/grasset.htm\">the original</a> on 5 February 2007.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Books+and+Writers+%27%27%28kirjasto.sci.fi%29%27%27&amp;rft.atitle=Jos%C3%A9+Ortega+y+Gasset&amp;rft.aulast=Liukkonen&amp;rft.aufirst=Petri&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kirjasto.sci.fi%2Fgrasset.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADeath+of+the+novel\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://forum.llc.ed.ac.uk/si1/sieg.html\">[1]</a>: <i>D\u00f6blin finds fault with the novel, since it focuses on individual characters or in its classic form of the Bildungsroman even recounts the education of the one protagonist. In his critique of the novel as genre, D\u00f6blin echoes considerations of both the literary discourse in Germany, which reflects on what has been called the 'crisis of narration', and the philosophical debate on the vanishing subject.</i></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/John_Barth\" title=\"John Barth\">John Barth</a>, \"<a href=\"/wiki/The_Literature_of_Exhaustion\" title=\"The Literature of Exhaustion\">The Literature of Exhaustion</a>\", <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Atlantic\" title=\"The Atlantic\">The Atlantic</a>,</i> 1967</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Heidenreich, Rosmarin. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=vdDfAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA9&amp;lpg=PA9\"><i>The Postwar Novel in Canada: Narrative Patterns and Reader Response</i></a>. Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press. p.&#160;9. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1554587018\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1554587018\">1554587018</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">24 June</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Postwar+Novel+in+Canada%3A+Narrative+Patterns+and+Reader+Response&amp;rft.pages=9&amp;rft.pub=Wilfrid+Laurier+Univ.+Press&amp;rft.isbn=1554587018&amp;rft.aulast=Heidenreich&amp;rft.aufirst=Rosmarin&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DvdDfAgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA9%26lpg%3DPA9&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADeath+of+the+novel\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Delahoyde, Dr. Michael. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://public.wsu.edu/~delahoyd/20th/robbe.html\">\"Robbe-Grillet, Jealousy\"</a>. <i>Washington State University</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">22 June</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Washington+State+University&amp;rft.atitle=Robbe-Grillet%2C+Jealousy&amp;rft.aulast=Delahoyde&amp;rft.aufirst=Dr.+Michael&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fpublic.wsu.edu%2F~delahoyd%2F20th%2Frobbe.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ADeath+of+the+novel\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Eugenio Bolongaro, <i>Italo Calvino and the Compass of Literature</i> (2003), p. 130.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://ethics.sandiego.edu/video/APA/Pacific/2001/Pippin/Robert%20Pippin,%20Response%20to%20Critics.html\">Robert Pippin, Response to Critics</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://books.guardian.co.uk/critics/reviews/0,5917,219810,00.html\">Ravelstein by Saul Bellow | Critics | Guardian Unlimited Books</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://www.ptwi.com/~bobkat/observer1.html\">[2]</a>, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Observer\" title=\"The New York Observer\">The New York Observer</a></i>, October 13, 1997</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Self, Will. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/may/02/will-self-novel-dead-literary-fiction\">\"The novel is dead (this time it's for real)\"</a>. <i>The Observer</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrie